Grafana Alert Routing to Internal Alert System
Dummy runbook v2 — generic pattern for all Grafana alerts (pilot: Airflow CPU Utilization)

1. Purpose
Grafana alerts need to be sent to an internal alert system. The internal alert system receives events through a Lambda function created by the DaaS/internal alert system developer. Grafana must send alerts in a JSON format that the Lambda can parse and transform into the internal alert object.
This version replaces the earlier single-alert approach. It defines one generic pattern that works for all (~260) Grafana alerts, including rules that do not define custom labels, and it does so without changing anything for the people who currently receive these alerts by email through SNS. The Airflow CPU Utilization alert is used as the pilot.
2. Design Principles
Additive, not destructive. The existing SNS topic, its email subscribers, and the human-readable message they receive today are not modified. The JSON feed is delivered through a new, separate SNS topic that only the SQS queue subscribes to.
Generic template. The contact point message template contains no alert-specific values. It serializes whatever labels and annotations each alert actually has. Every Grafana alert automatically carries at least the alertname and grafana_folder labels, so even rules with no custom labels produce a usable payload.
Tolerant Lambda. The Lambda treats all custom labels as optional and applies defaults or a lookup table when a label is missing. An alert must never be dropped because a label is absent.
Gradual adoption. Teams add the standard label set to their rules over time. As labels appear, the Lambda's defaults are used less. No big-bang migration of 260 rules is required.
