         -> Lambda: example-alert-transformer-lambda
         -> Internal Alert System API
         -> Internal Alert UI
A Grafana contact point can contain multiple integrations, and every integration fires for each notification. This is what makes the design additive: email and JSON are two integrations on the same contact point, each with its own topic and its own message template.
4. Why This Design
The Lambda needs json.loads(message) to succeed, so its input must be strict JSON. Email recipients need readable text, not JSON. One message template cannot serve both audiences, so the delivery paths are split: the existing topic keeps the default Grafana message for humans, and the new topic carries JSON for machines.
Hard-coding label values in the template (the earlier approach) only works for one alert rule and cannot distinguish multiple firing instances. Because roughly 260 rules share contact points and most rules do not define the full label set, the template must be generic and the Lambda must supply defaults.
5. AWS Setup — New JSON Topic
Create a new SNS topic: EXAMPLE-PRD-Alerts-JSON.
Subscribe the existing SQS queue (example-prd-alerts-queue) to the new topic.
Enable raw message delivery on the SQS subscription. Without it, SNS wraps the payload in a notification envelope and the Lambda receives the JSON as a string inside the "Message" field instead of at the top level.
Do not add email subscribers to this topic.
Leave the existing EXAMPLE-PRD-Alerts topic and its email subscriptions untouched.
