7. Generic JSON Template
Paste the following into the Message field of the JSON SNS integration only. It contains no alert-specific values and is shared by all rules.
{
  "alerts": [
    {{- range $i, $alert := .Alerts }}
    {{- if $i }},{{ end }}
    {
      "status": {{ printf "%q" $alert.Status }},
      "fingerprint": {{ printf "%q" $alert.Fingerprint }},
      "labels": {
        {{- range $j, $pair := $alert.Labels.SortedPairs }}
        {{- if $j }},{{ end }}
        {{ printf "%q" $pair.Name }}: {{ printf "%q" $pair.Value }}
        {{- end }}
      },
      "annotations": {
        {{- range $j, $pair := $alert.Annotations.SortedPairs }}
        {{- if $j }},{{ end }}
        {{ printf "%q" $pair.Name }}: {{ printf "%q" $pair.Value }}
        {{- end }}
      }
    }
    {{- end }}
  ]
}
How it works:
Iterates over every alert instance in the notification, so multiple simultaneous alerts produce multiple array entries.
Serializes every label and annotation the alert actually has. Nothing is hard-coded, so the same template serves all 260 rules.
printf "%q" escapes quotes, backslashes, and newlines, keeping the rendered body valid JSON even when descriptions contain special characters.
fingerprint is a stable per-alert hash provided by Grafana; the internal system can use it as the dedup key for create-vs-update. If your Grafana version does not expose .Fingerprint, delete that line — the Lambda falls back to a hash of alertname plus labels.
A label a rule does not define simply does not appear in the payload (rather than appearing as an empty string), which makes "missing" detectable on the Lambda side.
